      <abstract>
        <p>James R Oestreich reviews recording Fasch: Concertos and Orchestral Suites, with Ensemble Barocco Padovano Sans Souci, under direction of Aldo Fiorentin (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>FASCH: CONCERTOS AND ORCHESTRAL SUITES  Soloists; Ensemble Barocco Padovano Sans Souci, conducted by Aldo Fiorentin. Dynamic DS 201; CD.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>FASCH: CONCERTOS AND ORCHESTRAL SUITES  Soloists; Ensemble Barocco Padovano Sans Souci, conducted by Aldo Fiorentin. Dynamic DS 201; CD.</p>
        <p>To appreciate fully the achievement of groups like Musica Antiqua Koln in bringing such historically remote composers as Heinichen and Hasse back to life, it is necessary to hear recordings like this.</p>
        <p>It is never less than serviceable, to be sure; indeed, it is much like most of the recordings from which we geezers learned Baroque music in the first place: loose in ensemble and droopy in intonation, lacking the vivifying excitement that only crack performance can produce (not that it always does). Things get especially gamy (the game being duck) when Giuseppe Nalin, the oboe soloist enters the picture.</p>
        <p>No matter. Johann Friedrich Fasch, a contemporary of Bach and Handel, is well worth getting to know in depth, as Dynamic has already shown with a similar CD by Carlos Gubert and the Accademia Bach. These are said to be first recordings, and probably are, since the scores were transcribed from manuscipt by the conductor, Aldo Fiorentin.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
